One day your child makes a new friend. A little Black boy they met at school. You notice that your kid never mentions their difference in skin color. When describing him, they point out his cool shoes or hat, but never the very obvious. And you might be tempted to think, “Wow. My child does not see color. They don’t even know that their friend is Black.”

We must know that this can’t actually be true. 
Because from when our kids are little we give them words to describe the world around them. We point out the green trees, blue skies & yellow daisies. We quiz them on the colors of their Hotwheels cars & they nail every one of them.

And if that’s not enough, research tells us that babies as young as 6 months can distinguish skin color among ethnic groups.

It’s time to remove colorblindness from our thoughts & words.

You’ve given them the ability to talk about all the things in their own little world. But if you’ve been silent about the different skin tones there are & why they exist, your kids won’t have the language to do that themselves.

The way you react when your child does point out skin color is so crucial. If they are hushed when they say their friend looks dirty all the time, they will think something is wrong. Instead, use that awkward moment as a teachable one. “Oh that’s not dirt, that is beautiful brown skin that comes from something called melanin. Your skin is also a shade of brown from melanin too, but your friend has lots more because his ancestors lived in a really hot place and the melanin in their skin helped protect them from the sun.” Even better, have these conversations early so they can have the language to describe & appreciate what they are seeing in others.

Be excited that your child gets to meet a new friend who does not look like them. Normalize those differences by pointing out the beautiful shades of brown there are in all of us.

#melaninpoppin #blackisbeautiful #loveoneanother #lovewins #advocatelikeamother

December usually feels a lot like a potent extension of motherhood…Compounded into daily acts of giving, sacrifice, late nights and effort that mostly goes unnoticed.

But today I read that magic could also be a synonym of love. So if a sacrifice as small as twinkling lights all over a bedroom or one as large as searching the ends of the earth for that ridiculously overpriced pair of shoes—somehow spells out to my children how much I love them, well, then I am here to deliver all the magic I can.

And now I can’t help but wonder if Christmas is an extension of God’s parenting…The magic of a holiday that would become a potent reminder of His love.

It always starts with the bad attitude and the complaining about wanting to go anywhere else but here. And it always ends with grateful goodbyes and full hearts.
And what happens in between? It’s magic. 

“I slept and dreamt that life was joy. I awoke and saw that life was service. I acted and behold, service was joy.” -Tagore

When your teenager asks which orphanage we will visit next, you know there’s something special happening in that heart. Our second service trip to an orphanage with @childshopefoundation was incredible.

It was one of those moments that stopped me dead in my tracks. You see, adoption has always been a quiet melody playing in the background of our lives. 

But for my boys, especially this one, I know it can feel more like the elephant in the room… A constant feeling of being different from the people around you.

And so we must take extra care to make sure he knows there is always room enough for his differences and that belonging is taking up just as much space.

I hope he feels it here, in moments like this, watching an episode of Black-ish together and letting his Dad comb out his hair. 

I hope when he looks back on his childhood he will understand that it’s okay that our family wasn’t forged out of sameness. Because it was forged out of something even stronger—the labor of love.

 Where we belong in this world is not just a function of the blood in our veins, it’s a choice. Belonging, acceptance, connection—This is a gift we give each other and I know it’s one that we are hell bent on giving our boys for their entire lives.

After my loved ones, I would grab these first in a fire.

I called time of death on my long term memory years ago. I’ve been doodling our days in planners since 2020 and we all love to look back at the small moments that so easily slip from memory. In the bigger weekly sections of the planner, I also jot down things I learn or more detail of a day, funny things the boys said, or the things God whispered to me.

A treasure trove of little moments slowly adding up to one beautiful life I’ll never forget.

Adoption has taught me many things. 

But this lesson might be my favorite:

No matter your differences, you can choose to love and be loved.
In looks
In ideas
In beliefs
In life

I can’t think of a better gift life has to offer than the opportunity to look at the world through the lens of another.

One of us (ahem, the man child) would never admit just how magical it was.

On another note, I love that trees understand life’s seasons. Trees know when to blossom and when to be patient. They know that growth is not about rushing through change. It’s about being patient in the season they are in and trusting that during those hard and dark winters they will be okay because they will blossom again when it’s time. Trees have faith. And you can too beautiful you.
God spoiled the ending for us a little bit by showing us vear after vear that no matter what “season” vou are experiencing in life right now, you will survive it. You will bloom again and the beauty that will be restored to your life will be even more evident because of the “winter” you are experiencing now.
Pinky promise.

Next time you come across one of these, be sure to tell your kids about the black man or woman to thank for it.

Most of us are familiar with the greats of Black History. Frederick Douglass, Martin Luther King, Malcom X, Harriet Tubman, Rosa Parks, etc. The abolitionists and dreamers who moved mountains with their courage and resilience. I don’t know about you, but just learning the names of the heroes of black history means I learned to only ever associate the African American race with slavery or civil rights movements. And although what these people did is truly incredible, I want my son to also know that he came from a long and rich history of some of the greatest minds out there...many who continue to go unnoticed and unrecognized for their contributions. And I want my white son to know that the things he enjoys today are in large part due to the genius of his brother’s race as well as his own.

Leave your favorite innovations in the comments!

When he was in 4th grade, at the peak of his beautiful twists, we were sent an email from the school letting us know that Eli’s hair did not fit the dress code and was a “distraction.”

Thankfully by then I had spent enough time learning about the healthiest styles for his texture and the history of black hair to know how respond to ignorance with education. Thankfully the school was apologetic and open to learning as well. 

But it wasn’t until just LAST year, (yep. March 2022) that The CROWN Act was passed.  A law that prohibits the denial of employment and educational opportunities because of hair texture or protective hairstyles including braids, locs, twists or bantu knots.

The Crown Act, which stands for “Creating a Respectful and Open World for Natural Hair,” is the first legislation in U.S. history to ban discrimination based on hair style and texture. However, It has only been signed into law in 18 states so far. There is still work to do Nationwide. 

Whether you are in a classroom, or in the workplace, when you see someone rocking their crown with their head held high, send a nod of support instead of a look of judgement. Because now you know that hair has a rich history.  Now you know it symbolizes empowerment, individuality and once the very survival of strong black men and women. 

Also we could never help him be proud of his hair without friends like @kkuts11 keeping him fresh.

He was born into this world with a whole lot of extra love surrounding him. All these years later, and it only continues to grow stronger. We look forward to this darling and creative box from his biological grandma every year.

The good list: February sunshine. Your mother’s home cooked meals•Handstands with crooked legs•Pounding cleats throwing grass like confetti•Wobbly puppy legs•A newborn’s perfection•When your own strength catches you by surprise.

I hope your parents have already told you how the world may treat Eli differently than it does you.

But just in case, here are some things to remember when hanging out with our guy..

{Please appreciate his color and culture. Learn about the black people he admires & his history.

If you notice his girlfriend’s or new friends parents treating him differently, please vouch for him. Help them see the same big-hearted friend you know. The one who eats at your table, sits next to you at church, and came to your Spiderman birthday party. The little boy you’ve always known, is just that same bigger boy now, so help others see him as you do.}

You have no idea what it means to me to know that when I send my son out into the world, I can rest assured that he is being looked after and loved by friends like you.

In a world where headlines are pushing the message that all hope is lost, it’s hard for me to see the good around me.

But today my eye caught sight of it in the dog treat our UPS driver always leaves. 

And it made me wonder…If the goodness of people can show up daily in bite size doses, how much good am I missing sight of? 

I’m recommitting to recognizing it. 

I had the privilege of hearing Chanel Miller (author of, Know My Name) share some thoughts during a book club meeting and loved the perspective she gave of navigating what can feel like crippling hopelessness. 

“All of us are sitting on the power to save someone’s life each day. We can’t  know the effect that our hello or smile or “have a good day,” has on the people around us. 

Do not become the ones who hurt you. Stay tender with your power. Never fight to injure, fight to uplift. Fight because you know that in this life, you deserve safety, joy, and freedom. Fight because it is your life.

We may spend half our time wandering around, wondering what we’re even doing here, why it’s worth the effort. But living is an incredible thing, just to have been here, to have felt, if only briefly, the volume and depth of others’ empathy. I wrote, most of all, to tell you I have seen how good the world could be.” @chanel_miller

Our boys challenged my husband and I to a photography competition. We split up in teams headed to a park and these were the results.

When most kids look at a family photo they might see a piece of themselves in the features of the ones they love. A tangible and genetic privilege that grounds them in a sense of belonging.

We’ve obviously never shared this tangible connection with our boys and it takes effort to bridge that gap to the less obvious ways they belong to us. 

But despite not sharing our genetic codes that physically say “you are mine”—there are moments like this photo challenge when I find them doing or loving something in the exact same way I do and I am reminded all over again that family isn’t forged out of sameness. 

Where we belong in this world is not just a function of the blood in our veins, it’s a choice. Belonging, acceptance, connection—This is a gift we give each other.

Family is forged out of the labor of love. Let’s remember that in our own nuclear families and in our human family as well.

Easter egg hunts in what remains of winter and I can’t think of a better way to be reminded that Sunday always comes.

If you are still experiencing a “winter” of your life, hang in there beautiful you. You will take root and find the surface again. Proof of redemption is written in the process of nature itself. Trust that there is a pattern, a rhythm, a beauty, a natural rise and fall to your life as well. That the One holding together the Earth, is also capable of holding together your heart. The one making this world and all of it's seasons so achingly beautiful, is also working to make your life beautiful, too. I know this because these boys right here are MY Sunday and they came after a very long and bleak Friday in my life.

No matter how dark and deep your sorrow, there is even more light and love and hope ahead of you, all because of a Savior who died and lived again for you.

That's my truest story, but whatever God looks like for you today, claim the peace that comes with nature's lesson--that no matter how dark it is now, you will rise again.

It’s the way of Heaven and Earth.

#easter2023 #becauseofhim #helives

Even though my body didn’t grow a baby in the traditional way, I’m thankful my heart did.

Even though I wasn’t meant to wrap my arms around my stomach and feel the signs of life in there, I thank those arms for being made to hold the boys that someone else could not.

I may not have heard their heart beat through a monitor, but my ears have listened well to all of their fears and dreams from the deepest parts of their little hearts. 

My body never failed. Not for one second. Rather, it prepared me. The emptiness in my womb made all the room necessary to grow my babies in my heart. 

I know that if God wouldn’t have spent that extra time on me, I wouldn’t have known what it meant to be asked to love a baby that someone else brought into this world as my own. I wouldn’t have known that I could. 

I’m thinking of all you beautiful 1 in 8s out there who are experiencing your own wait right now. Whether waiting for a child who carries your genes or another’s. It can be one lonely road, but take comfort in the statistics. They are proof that you are not alone in this. And while you wait for whatever miracle God has in store for you, rest assured that He is making something beautiful out of this situation & of you.

I’m so fortunate to be able to peer into the eyes of one beautiful boy who holds no gene of mine & love him with an overwhelming love that makes me want to change the world for him. Learning from him, loving him, has changed me in a way that nothing else could.

Every person needs and deserves the opportunity to see the world through another’s view. We cannot be aware of the realities that living with a particular skin color, disability, orientation, or identity in this world can mean for others if we don’t have an opportunity to hear from them. And we cannot leave the marginalized feeling alone and isolated by taking away the perspectives of others walking in their same shoes.

We cannot defeat the evils of this world without understanding them first. That is why I have partnered with @campaignsharedfuture as they work to ensure inclusive and accessible education for ALL and fight for equitable, anti-racist programs, practices, and policies that sustain schools and ensure opportunity for every child.

Our kids need to learn the full history that shaped his country. The good and the bad. So that they can take what we’ve learned from the past and forge a better future for all of us. We need their big beautiful hearts to show us the way.

I couldn’t be more grateful that God wrote this contingency into my life’s plan.

I’m learning more and more that the love language of Heaven is patience. That God’s promises are rarely ever found in the miracles we were banking on, but down in the nitty gritty, break your heart wide open circumstances that He works together for our good.

If we are not actively showing our children that love is inclusive of every human being, the world will step in with it’s harmful narratives and teach them the lie that some are not worthy of love because of their differences. We cannot afford to let children grow up with those messages.

Everyone has a right to learn about the variety of human experiences and perspectives that books provide. Everyone deserves to learn from those who are experiencing life differently.

 @campaignsharedfuture is fighting for just that. A non-partisan organization that focuses all efforts on supporting high-quality K-12 education: they believe every child has the right to access an inclusive, non-discriminatory academic environment.

How can we as parents make a difference?
 ✔️Support your kid’s school librarians, teachers, staff, and administrators when faced with these issues.
 ✔️Show up to school board meetings and let your voice be heard.
 ✔️Get involved by joining the school board. Attend meetings and invite other parents to join you.
 ✔️If you’re able, why not run for your local school board?

Click the link in my profile to see how we can each make an impact where we are and support those who are truly seeking to serve the best interests of our children.

Creamy tomato basil soup recipe

2-3 large tomatoes 
12 ounces cherry tomatoes 
2 small shallots 
1-2 garlic bulb
3 TB olive oil 
1 bunch basil
1/4 c. Heavy cream
Salt and pepper, seasonings
Parmesan cheese and basil for toppings 

-Preheat oven to 400
-Peel outer layers of whole head of garlic-leave cloves intact
-In a large baking dish add tomatoes, shallots, half fresh basil, and head of garlic
-drizzle with olive oil and seasonings 
-bake 35-40 min until tender
-remove from oven and cook slightly 
-remove garlic cloves and add rest of mixture to blender with heavy cream.

Color craving has been satisfied. ✔️ 

I spend a lot of time soaking my joints here during Fall and winter and I needed a cozy, colorful place to relax.

Paint color is Glidden sailors coat, satin finish.

Frames and prints are thrifted or ones I had around the house.

When doing a gallery wall I always lay the frames out on my bed or a similar size floor space and arrange to my liking. Then I snap a picture and recreate it on the wall.

I love hanging pictures of my boys and being reminded of the best parts of motherhood.

Adoption made me a mother over 15 years ago. I’ve collected every hug, kiss and “I love you mom” along the way. I put them on the shelf next to my many motherhood badges of honor. The up-all-nights with them, the feedings and diaper changes, lullabys, tickle fights and bedtime stories. I’ve displayed every “real mom” moment for my heart to see because I knew one day those babies would need a mother who is confident in their love for her while they grow through the complexities of being adopted.
 
In adoption, and I guess in all parenting really, our kids need to know we are ready for their questions and can hold space for their silence. They need to know we can contain the fire of their hurt when it comes, even if we are the ones who gets burned. They need to know that they are safe to wonder over all the might-have-beens in their life.

They need to know it’s okay to miss the woman who brought them into this world, even if they don’t know her. And most of all, they need to know there is enough room in their hearts to hold the love of their two mothers.

Love never fails. Not once, not ever.

Love creates a sense of belonging that goes beyond genetics and adoption has proven this time and time again.

Just leaving this here for the daily reminder I know I need. 

#motherhoodunited #boymom #adoptivemom

He laughed and said “I’m about to be real blunt right now, but a white girl from Utah trying to teach her son how to be Black is like a one legged man stepping into an ass-whooping contest. You’ll fall flat on your face because it’s just not possible.” 

Also, my therapist is Black and can say this.
But then he also gave me this advice that I’ve relied on since then:

“You just worry about raising him to be a good man. His Blackness is already inside of him and he will figure out how to develop that on his own. He will find the parts of the culture and history he connects with and the parts that he doesn’t. You can’t teach Black because there is not one way to be Black.”

I’ll never how hard and complex it feels to constantly have your differences on display, I only know how grateful I am for the friends and role models in his life that he can see himself in. The ones who relate to the skin he is in, in every sense of the word and contribute to his confidence and the incredibly good kid he already is.

How I ever got lucky enough to take the front row seat and watch him grow, I’ll never know.

#blackboyjoy #blackandproud #blackexcellence #transracialadoption

It’s funny how life turns out sometimes:

It turns out that the most remarkable thing I will ever do will be to spend my days loving these people. Not from the perspective of a 3-inch square on social media, but in our least Instagrammable moments--in the quiet and ordinary parts of our every day where I am reminded of the years I spent praying for everything I have now, and knowing that my life looks nothing like what I asked for.

Turns out it's been one of the greatest blessings of my life to love someone who doesn't think and believe like I do. That has since moved beyond my marriage and spread out into the big wide world of appreciating the differences in all humans. It has made all the difference in my life.

Turns out it's possible to disagree deeply and love deeply at the same time. It's been a gift to be able to evaluate our beliefs and recognize that we didn't marry each other for a single one of them. Even though we use different words for him, it's been a gift to find God every where.

Turns out I wouldn't change the fact that I didn’t see either of my children come into this world. I would every time, want the first person to love them to keep those three sacred days of their lives to herself, after what she gave me for the rest of mine. 

Turns out that this life is my wildest dream come true and I am grateful every day that God pried my fingers off the life I was holding on to so hard and placed this one in my hands instead.

Tell me something that turned out differently for you in life. ⬇️

Ghosty S’mores recipe: 👻
Cast iron skillet 
1 bag marshmallows or ghost peeps
2c. Semi-sweet chocolate chips
1/4c. Heavy cream
Mini chocolate chips for eyes and mouth
Graham crackers or cookies for serving

Preheat oven to 450

In bottom of the skillet, spread out chocolate chips and pour cream on top.

Cover completely with single layer of marshmallows. 

Place some mini chips for eyes and mouth. 

Bake until chocolate is melted, and ghosts brown 8-10 minutes 

Serve with a plate of graham crackers or cookies for dipping.

The good lately: A sore back well worth the quality time. Massage as payment. Building sandcastles in the middle of a dirt road. Realizing that teenage rough-housing is equivalent to an affectionate hug. Sun bathing on boulders. Childhood confessions around a fire. Mom and sister snuggle sessions. The magic of endless freckles and twinkle lights. Strolling memory lane on the Christmas tree. Wide open spaces and not enough space. Evenings spent in cozy light with the urge to never leave. Attempting to love perfectly, falling short magnanimously.

I will never grow tired of discovering more about my children through the genetics they inherited from another family.

Every difficult emotion at play with their adoptions has been met with equal amounts of love and healing and I could not be more honored to be the one chosen to do this life with all of them.

It’s the truest thing I know.

If you are still waiting to be a mother, or wanting to be a mom of one more, or missing the baby you never got to raise... Please remember that you just never know what your family photo hanging on the walls of heaven is going to look like. I promise it will beautiful.

Most definitely my less than serious attitude towards school has set the stage for imperfect test scores and grades and it’s okay, because all their knowing, their quiet observing, nurturing, empathetic abilities to hurt with others who are hurting…It’s a magic kind of smart that will take them far in life.

Hey you mama. Yes you, who chose to stay home with your kids all day e’ry day. 

You with the messy hair and the macaroni Picasso stain on the pajamas you’re still wearing. 

Next time someone asks you what you do for a living and you are tempted to say “Im just a stay-at-home mom,” be sure to finish off that sentence with “in the same way that Clark Kent is JUST a reporter.” 

Because even if the world doesn’t always, and your kids don’t now, someday they will recognize and appreciate the days and lifetime you spent busting out of the phone booth for them.

They’ll remember the sleds you carried to the top of the hill, the snow clothes you slipped on and off 100 times a day, the times you were waiting at the bottom of the hill, the slide, or their hardest moments. Where they always knew you were a soft place to land.

And to the mamas who kiss your babies goodbye every morning to go provide for them and then come home to do what I have an entire day to do, in just a few hours.... don’t think there is a super hero in the world that compares to you.

I once read that the “the fabric of who we are is not the sum of what we can remember, it’s made up of experiences we’ve had, the people we love, and what we’ve done with the time we’ve been given.” 

And I’m so grateful for that truth because even though time steals much of all we wish we could hold onto, at the very least, we are left with everything those moments are made up of.

The good list:
Spontaneous mid-week adventures, hot springs that heal, wide open spaces, cotton candy on tap, treasures unearthed at goodwill bins, brother sleepovers, winter sleigh rides and a New Year with an empty calendar waiting to be filled.

If you are an adoptive, foster or bonus mama of any kind, chances are you will hear this question at some point in this mothering gig. I'll be honest. It stings the same every time. Especially when it's asked during the most real motherhood moments; like in line at a grocery store while my kid is screaming for the giant sucker at the top of his lungs. Or at a doctor's office with a feverish baby on my lap and bags under my eyes from staying up all night with him. Or even now at soccer games after my voice is hoarse from cheering or at a restaurant during a particularly hard conversation over Oreo shakes.

If that isn't enough to light up a billboard on my heart that says "I'm his real mom" I don't know what is.
